gn=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub101.ezboard.com/bthetribunaldotorg.showUserPublicProfile?gid=sashanna>Sashanna</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>l33t board camper</span><br>  Posts: 300<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(3/25/03 5:16 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub101.ezboard.com/fthetribunaldotorgfrm36.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=544.topic>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> We have a problem</span><hr size=1> For once I am going to drop the bullshit rhetoric that has punctuated previous posts of mine because I think that we have a serious problem.  By “we” I mean as a citizen of a Western nation because, like it or not, we are now all in the same boat together.<br>
<br>
The problem is this:  the Coalition forces have seized control of the air and the deserts.  They have, to date, demonstrated a complete inability to seize control of urban areas.  The sole urban area currently held is Umm Qasr which is a very small port city with a population of around 40,000 people (please correct me if that figure is wrong).  <br>
<br>
The crux is that Umm Qasr is a major strategic objective for the Coalition forces because, as Iraq’s only deep water port, it will control access for both reinforcements and humanitarian aid.  On cnn.com it is reported today that there are still “pockets of resistance” in Umm Qasr.  This indicates to me that it is likely that Coalition forces only control a portion of the city, likely the area immediately around the port itself.  <br>
<br>
Given the importance of Umm Qasr to the greater war effort, its relative small size, and the difficulty with which Coalition forces have had in controlling it, this does not bode well for larger centres such as Basra (population 1.4 million) or Baghdad (population 7 million).<br>
<br>
We have all learned from Somalia that Apaches &amp; Blackhawks have limited utility in providing support to ground forces fighting street battles.  They are capable of blazing fire lanes and wiping out angry mobs but are ill suited to dealing with small groups of combatants, especially ones wearing civilian clothing.  Fighter jets are completely ill suited to urban combat for obvious reasons unless ones objective is to exterminate all life in certain city blocks.<br>
<br>
This war has been sold to the world as a “war of liberation” for the Iraqi people.  The Coalition forces cannot engage in wholesale bombing of the civilian population unless they can successfully convince the world that the inherent character of the war has changed.  This is not likely to be an easy sell.<br>
<br>
This means that, failing a massive uprising of the people of Basra and Baghdad, the Coalition forces are going to have to fight their way through these urban centres.  Somalia taught us that you need heavy armour to support infantry in house to house fighting – tanks can blow their way through walls and shoot at angles that helicopters just cannot reach.  That being said, heavy armour isnt necessarily the solution that one might have hoped.  The Abrahms tanks are too wide to fit down many of Basra’s and Baghdad’s streets and their exhaust (which vents at the rear) can reach 1000 degrees, meaning that troops cannot effectively shelter from small arms fire behind them.  While Bradley Fighting Vehicles are smaller and capable of providing shelter, they lack the punch of the Abrahms tanks.  <br>
<br>
Before a massive uprising of the people can occur, the Coalition forces must demonstrate their capability to actually win the war.  Many high ranking Iraqis are currently sitting on the fence waiting to see which way the wind will blow.  The problem is that the majority are currently more afraid of Saddam Hussein then they are of the Coalition.<br>
<br>
This leaves the Coalition in a Catch-22 situation.  In order to demonstrate their capability of winning the war, they must seize control of a large urban centre.  They cannot seize a large urban centre without the active support of the local population.  <br>
<br>
With approximately 185,000 troops in the field, the Coalition forces are technologically superior but outnumbered.  In house to house fighting, technology provides only a limited advantage, which, in my opinion, is insufficient to overcome the resistance that will be offered by the approximately 75,000 elite Iraqi troops and additional 200,000+ regular troops plus an unknown number of civilians and party loyalists in roaming militias.  <br>
<br>
A US General has admitted that the Coalition does not currently have enough troops in the field to besiege Baghdad.  While additional reinforcements being rerouted through the Suez Canal from Turkey will help, it will still not be enough.<br>
<br>
The Coalition faces calling up additional troops from the US, UK and Australia solely to mount a siege of Baghdad.  In order to actually seize control of the city through house to house fighting, the Coalition will need, at the very least, to have the same number of troops that it used to route Iraq from Kuwait (500,000).  <br>
<br>
I don’t know what percentage of US military assets are currently committed in Iraq but I suspect that the Coalition forces would have difficulty doubling their current numbers, let alone trebling them to reach 500,000.<br>
<br>
Where does that leave us as citizens of the Western world?  <br>
<br>
Well it leaves us in a stalemate in Iraq which would be a globally destabilising event.  A stalemate would be perceived as a loss by the general public which would likely mean the end of the Bush, Blair and Howard administrations.  It would also mean a long and protracted war with great civilian suffering.  The end is difficult to predict but it is conceivable that mounting public pressure could force Coalition troops out of Iraq without having removed Saddam Hussein.  This would represent a massive loss of face for the Western world and throw into question the current unipolar model.<br>
<br>
For the sake of all of us I hope that I am horribly wrong and that the war will be swift and just.  That being said, I have deep reservations otherwise.  <br>
