<br>
You are right in saying that we don't have the manpower to occupy every single Iraqi city, but we simply won't need to.  Once the regime is gone, we will have two things:  international support for any policing actions necessary, and a lack of significant organized resistant necessitating any extended military occupation.<br>
<br>
German technological superiority in Stalingrad?  It was largely nonexistent, what little they had was largely unimportant.  Our technological superiority is so overwhelming and complete as to  be almost ridiculous.  Our men are better trained, better equipped, better led, better motivated, and better supported, each to several degrees of magnitude.<br>
<br>
Everyone keeps screaming, &quot;Mogadishu!!&quot; when the only similarities between that situation and Baghdad is the fact that they're both cities.  There is no civilian opposition.  Umm Qasr?  Exactly how much difficulty have we had controlling it?  Of course there will be &quot;difficulty&quot;, to expect anything else in wartime is silly.  That doesn't mean that we aren't overcoming that difficulty effectively.<br>
<br>
Anyway, the point is, pray for them, but don't worry about it.  Let the military do their thing.  At this point there's nothing we can do anyway but watch and wait.  But be confident.  Cost vs. benefit dictates that we won't attempt to capture cities like Basra while there is still organized Saddamite resistance, but that doesn't mean that we are incapable of doing so.  Personally, I think we've got a lot more up our sleeves as well.  =) <p><!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.visveres.myguilds.com/sigs/caledhon.gif" style="border:0;"/><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub101.ezboard.com/bthetribunaldotorg.showUserPublicProfile?gid=elcheproudfoot>Elche Proudfoot</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/white_redspot.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Mmmmm lobster</span><br>  Posts: 1179<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(3/25/03 8:25 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub101.ezboard.com/fthetribunaldotorgfrm36.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=544.topic&index=5>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.woc.org/public/oneirodynia/images/srllogo.GIF height=180 width=180></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: We have a problem</span><hr size=1> wrong forum pls! <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#4D4D4D><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub101.ezboard.com/bthetribunaldotorg.showUserPublicProfile?gid=loeganwolfheart>Loegan Wolfheart</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Please do things my way, thx.</span><br>  Posts: 2759<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(3/25/03 9:00 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub101.ezboard.com/fthetribunaldotorgfrm36.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=544.topic&index=6>Reply</a>    <br>ezSupporter<br> <BR><img src=http://loegan.homestead.com/files/rn.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: We have a problem</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Everyone keeps screaming, &quot;Mogadishu!!&quot; when the only similarities between that situation and Baghdad is the fact that they're both cities.</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
I think you misread my references to Mogadishu Cal. I was pointing to the fact that Mogadishu shows that the US public rails against relatively minor US losses when they are not completely behind the war/action. Right now the US is near 70% behind this, so it is not a problem. However if the war takes very long those numbers could be turned on their ear and they will be screaming to pull them out, without regard for the later consequences, just like they allowed them to be sent in without regard for future consequences to the region.<br>
<br>
That being said, Mogadishu was a failure in planning and execution, not a failure because we were unable to do the job. I don't think our urban war in Iraq can be compared to Mogadishu at all tactically, as these are completely different situations.<br>
<br>
As to the rest, I agree with you. I believe our failure to control the cities we are fighting in now is a matter of holding back, not because we can't. This matter of not harming civilians is making this a very, very difficult war to fight for our troops and one of the reasons I was so much against it. A soldier should only have to worry about defending themselves and their people and completing their mission, not fighting with kids gloves to avoid political fallout due to civilian casualties.<br>
<br>
I do think there will be much more civilian resistance than expected and I do believe civilians have been fighting already, despite the claims by US officials that <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>every</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> combatant in civilian clothes is a soldier in disguise. But I also think that when they discover they can't take these cities with kids gloves, they will ramp up the force used and eventually take them, even though it will increase collateral damage and civilian deaths.<br>
<br>
Unfortunately that will also ramp up the unrest in Arab states, but that was the risk going in and Bush knew it. Now we are trapped in a war that should have and could have been fought under much different circumstances.<br>
<br>
Bottom line though - I don't like the idea of sacrificing US/UK/Australian troops to fight a mickey mouse war where we are being too cautious and too nice. I hate losing civilians in war as much as anyone, but when the war is justified and not fought under the microscope we put ourselves under by being the aggressor, it does not cause the sort of reaction we have to worry about now.<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
