<br>
Incorrect.  The Coalition forces have chosen to bypass fortified urban areas in favor of a fast approach to Bagdad.<br>
<br>
<br>
Sashanna:<br>
On cnn.com it is reported today that there are still “pockets of resistance” in Umm Qasr. This indicates to me that it is likely that Coalition forces only control a portion of the city, likely the area immediately around the port itself. Given the importance of Umm Qasr to the greater war effort, its relative small size, and the difficulty with which Coalition forces have had in controlling it, this does not bode well for larger centres such as Basra (population 1.4 million) or Baghdad (population 7 million).<br>
<br>
True enough but, the reason there are still &quot;pockets of resistanc&quot; is the Coalition forces are being extremely careful not to inflict civilian casualties and to minimize exposing themselves to resistance.  This is a proven urban warfare tactic that uses time as an ally to break the will of the opposition.<br>
<br>
Sashanna:<br>
A US General has admitted that the Coalition does not currently have enough troops in the field to besiege Baghdad. While additional reinforcements being rerouted through the Suez Canal from Turkey will help, it will still not be enough.<br>
<br>
Yes and No, Sashanna.  The General said that we currently do not have the troops &quot;in the vicinity&quot; of Bagdad to &quot;fully besiege&quot; the city.  This means that we don't have the people/equipment needed to completely cut off the city from the outside.  This isn't neccessary in order to cut off supplies and force the citizens/military to surrender.<br>
<br>
I have no illusions that a house to house urban fight for control of Bagdad any urban area would be easy.  We do have the capability to cut them off from any reenforcements or supplies.  That is enough in that arena to force capitulation.  It may take weeks or &quot;possibly&quot; months but the end is certain once supplies have stopped moving.<br>
<br>
Let me also say, well done.  A very well thought through analysis of the situation.  You are absolutely correct on your overall view that either way this is not going to be an easy sell to the world community.  Unless the coalition comes up with some chemical and biological weapons of war to parade in front of the cameras.<br>
