<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>German technological superiority in Stalingrad? It was largely nonexistent, what little they had was largely unimportant. Our technological superiority is so overwhelming and complete as to be almost ridiculous. Our men are better trained, better equipped, better led, better motivated, and better supported, each to several degrees of magnitude.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
The numbers on Stalingrad are sketchy but it is an accepted figure that during the 6 month fighting in Stalingrad, over 1 million Soviets and Germans died fighting in the battle.  Soviets lost significantly more soldiers than Germans during the actual battle and about 200,000 more Germans died in the encirclement (Der Kessel) and 90,000 were taken prisoner by the Soviets which was about the same thing as being dead.<br>
<br>
Germans had a bigger technological advantage by far, not because the Soviet equipment was inferior but because the Soviets simply refused to send in massive reinforcements into the city.  The reason for this is that the factories were disassembled and moved to the Urals in 1941 and only begin to produce equipment by mid 1942.  Having limited amount of equipment (and when I mean equipment I mean primarily tanks and AT guns), they didn't want to send it in piecemeal and squander it in Stalingrad.  The planning for the Stalingrad counter offensive began as early as August of 1942 when the battle began and the prevailing opinion strongly reinforced by Zhukov was that it would be better to draw the Germans into Stalingrad and then encircle them, rather than repulse them out of Stalingrad with a head on assault.  There was also the consideration that a quick and rapid encirclement would cut off the escape route for Army Group B which was the Army Group that wheeled down to Georgia to grab the oil fields.  Assaulting the Germans head on would have taken long enough for Army Group B to return to Stalingrad and reinforce the 6th Army.<br>
<br>
Germans had the technological advantage at Stalingrad and air superiority, but it wasn't the sick and disgustingly huge advantage that the US military possesses currently in Iraq.  Also the Germans had no qualms about killing civilians while trying to take over the city, which is a latitude that US Military is not afforded.  When the battle started in mid August, Germans unleashed a 600 bomber raid over Stalingrad on Aug, 23, 1942 which killed over 40,000 civilians.<br>
<br>
And finally, in Stalingrad's urban fighting, technological advantage amounted to little.  After the first month of fighting and bombing, the streets were so congested with rubble that it was difficult if not impossible for tanks to get through.  Tanks were also incredibly vulnerable to ambushes and bazookas in city fighting because they are not designed for urban warfare, they are designed for field operations, rapid advances, encirclements, etc.  Artillery pieces mean little in urban assaults unless you have consolidated your defensive positions and merely using artillery pieces to level houses where enemy troops might be hiding.  Arguably, the only time that German technological superiority at Stalingrad made a difference was air power and Soviets lost huge amounts of materiel when trying to ferry troops, ammo, food and equipment across the Volga into the city.<br>
<br>
*  *  * <br>
<br>
As for urban fighting in the 21st century, I have no idea.  I think helicopters are going to prove incredibly useful for troop extraction and insertion and providing accurate air support, something which was unavailable in 1942.  Dropping dumb bombs from a bomber flying at 300 mph into a smoke filled city in 1942, trying to eliminate pockets of enemy resistance isn't exactly accurate. However, the current helicopter track record of the coalition isn't exactly encouraging.<br>
<br>
Frankly, I don't think it will come down to nasty urban fighting.  I think the Iraqis will likely fold by the time the coalition forces encircle Baghdad, simply because they have nothing to lose by surrendering, unlike the Soviets who knew that surrendering to the Germans would mean death anyway. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#333333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub101.ezboard.com/bthetribunaldotorg.showUserPublicProfile?gid=wenin>Wenin</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>I read porn more<BR>
than I play EQ...</span><br>  Posts: 1498<br> <font color=#FFFFFF>(3/25/03 10:37 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub101.ezboard.com/fthetribunaldotorgfrm36.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=544.topic&index=9>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.aradcliff.net/images/130.gif width=128 height=80></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: We have a problem</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr><br>
